1 San Juan juveniles

1.1 Freshwater - RST

Download raw purse seine data with genetic results from here: https://github.com/khdavidson/A20/blob/main/outputs/R_OUT%20-%20PFN_DFO_FTFjuvi_2023_verified%20WITH%20RESULTS.xlsx


1.1.1 Catch time series


Coho fry were by far the most common species encountered in the San Juan RST in 2023. Discerning any outmigration patters is difficult from the 2023 data as it was only run 2 days/week, but suggests an earlier install may be warranted in future years (see 1.1).

Figure 1.1: Total catch in the RST by salmon species and life stage. By-catch of trout and other non-fish species not shown.


1.1.2 Chinook catch and biosamples


In 2023 we caught relatively few Chinook in the RST. This is likely due to the trap only running 2 days/week as a pilot project. 2006 and 2007 catch data are given below, as well as Bedwell RST chinook catch, in order to compare timing and relative magnitude (see ??). Note that San Juan 2006 saw exceptionally high catch of chinook in one night, but was otherwise relatively consistent.

While the RST has had a fairly limited season at San Juan (no early February install or late June removal as at Sarita), the migration timing generally follows other WCVI systems, with many small fish leaving ~March-April.


Body size of San Juan chinook follow similar trends to other locations (Bedwell, Sarita), with early migrants being very small (mean FL = 40.9 +/- 2.21 mm and 0.57 +/- 0.08 g). The weight of natural San Juan Chinook is exceptionally small compared to the size of hatchery releases, which are typically 5-8 grams; even historical releases of fed fry were 1.5-2.5 g (see ??).

Only a small number of genetic samples were collected from the RST as we figured we did not need to bother running genetics from known San Juan origin juveniles upstream of the hatchery release location. However, of the 7 samples collected on one day, 3 were inconclusive/non-San Juan!

Figure 1.2: Genetic results from the San Juan RST 2003. Samples were not collected as they were not considered a focus of the project.

1.3.2 Catch composition

Most Chinook were encountered in late June, with a later bump in catch in mid-August. Forage fish (herring, smelts) were the most commonly encountered species, followed by Chinook and Sandlance. Purse seining likely started too late to encounter other salmon species (Coho, Chum) (see 1.3).

Figure 1.3: 2023 purse seine catch composition off Port Renfrew (Port San Juan).


1.3.2.1 Chinook catch and biosamples (in progress)

Very few adipose-clipped hatchery Chinook were encountered, but clipped fish were generally larger than unclipped fish. However, note that on July 7, all fish with DNA results returned were hatchery-origin San Juan (1 clipped, 20 unclipped), with the exception of 1 unclipped Washington-origin hatchery fish (Willapa River).

Figure 1.4: 2023 purse seine catch composition in Port Renfrew of chinook only.


Figure 1.5: Size of Chinook (marked and unmarked) in 2023 purse seine samples in Port Renfrew.

Figure 1.6: GSI stock comps only from the samples collected July 7. Reminaing samples still in process.
